ThinkPart(
    type='think',
    think='Now I have a very comprehensive understanding. Let me compile the rev
iew findings.\n\n**Critical Blocking Issues:**\n\n1. **MatchingGateway manual JW
T verification and CORS hack** - The `MatchingGateway` directly calls `jwt.verif
y(token, jwtConfig.secret)` instead of injecting `JwtService`, and uses the `aft
erInit` runtime hack to modify `engine.opts.cors`. Both are explicitly prohibite
d in `nestjs.md` sections "Gateway 认证与 CORS 规范" and are security/auth consi
stency issues.\n\n2. **ImBloc state leak across user sessions** - `ImBloc` is re
gistered as `registerLazySingleton` in `di.dart`. When a user logs out, `ImDisco
nnectRequested` is emitted which disconnects the socket but does NOT clear the i
nternal message caches (`_pendingMessages`, `_currentConversationId`). When a ne
w user logs in on the same app instance, the old user\'s messages and conversati
on state would still be present. This is a data privacy/security Blocking issue.
\n\n3. **Message `sequence_id` is not auto-incrementing** - The PRD explicitly r
equires: "`sequence_id` 使用数据库自增 `bigserial`，作为消息排序的唯一依据". But
the migration `20250426000000-CreateImTables.ts` creates `sequence_id BIGINT NOT
NULL` without `AUTO_INCREMENT`, and the entity uses `@Column("bigint")` without 
`@PrimaryGeneratedColumn`. The `im.service.ts` sets `sequence_id: 0` and relies 
on TypeORM or DB to auto-increment, but MySQL `BIGINT` without `AUTO_INCREMENT` 
won\'t do this. This is a Blocking functional issue because message ordering is 
broken.\n\nWait, let me re-check. In the migration:\n```sql\nsequence_id BIGINT 
NOT NULL,\n```\nAnd in the service:\n```typescript\nsequence_id: 0, // Will be r
eplaced by auto-increment\n```\nBut there\'s no auto-increment defined! This mea
ns all messages would have `sequence_id = 0`, breaking ordering and pagination. 
This is definitely Blocking.\n\nActually, TypeORM\'s `save()` might generate an 
auto-increment if the column is configured properly. But the entity doesn\'t use
`@PrimaryGeneratedColumn` or `@Generated("increment")`. The migration doesn\'t a
dd `AUTO_INCREMENT`. So this won\'t work. This is Blocking.\n\nWait, I need to b
e more careful. Looking at TypeORM docs, if you have `@Column("bigint")` without
any generation strategy, and you pass `0`, it will save `0`. The DB won\'t auto-
increment. Unless there\'s a trigger or default value. But the migration shows n
o `AUTO_INCREMENT` and no default. So yes, all messages would have `sequence_id 
= 0`, and the unique index on `(conversation_id, client_message_id)` would still
work for deduplication, but ordering by `sequence_id` would be completely broken
.\n\nActually, in MySQL you can only have one `AUTO_INCREMENT` per table, and it
must be part of a key. Since `id` is the primary key (char(36)), `sequence_id` c
annot be `AUTO_INCREMENT` in MySQL unless it\'s an indexed column... Actually in
MySQL, `AUTO_INCREMENT` doesn\'t have to be the primary key, but it must be inde
xed. So `sequence_id` could have `AUTO_INCREMENT` if it has an index. Looking at
the migration, `sequence_id` has `INDEX idx_messages_sequence_id (sequence_id)`.
So yes, it COULD be `AUTO_INCREMENT`. But the migration doesn\'t declare it.\n\n
